[2026-07-04T00:45:00] TASK 1A — PIVOT
Two architectural calls not fully pinned by SPEC.md/BuildPlan.md, made
explicit here rather than silently:
1. `SessionIdentityMiddleware` is written as a plain ASGI middleware
   (`__call__(scope, receive, send)`), not `starlette.middleware.base.
   BaseHTTPMiddleware` — the latter has well-documented issues with
   streaming responses/background tasks in this Starlette version, and
   §10.4's CSV export (`GET /api/v1/export.csv`, §8.8) will need to stream
   later. Avoiding the footgun now is cheaper than migrating later.
2. The OAuth request-token-to-session binding primitive (§10.2's addendum)
   is an in-process dict with a TTL, not a DB table. §10.2 explicitly
   allows either ("a short-lived row/cache entry"); given §10.6's no-Redis/
   no-background-queue stance and §12.2's single always-on backend process,
   in-process is the simpler choice with an identical security property
   (bound to session, single-use, short TTL). Documented in
   `OAuthSessionBinding`'s docstring, including the explicit caveat that
   this stops being correct if the backend ever runs multiple worker
   processes.
Also: interpreted BuildPlan's "generate this yourself... and document it in
backend/.env.example" for TOKEN_ENCRYPTION_KEY/SESSION_COOKIE_SECRET as
"document how to generate it, don't commit actual key material to git" —
committing real key bytes (even framed as a dev placeholder) into a
git-tracked file conflicts with "secrets never appear in code" as a general
principle. Instead: `.env.example` documents the exact one-line command to
generate each value locally, and both `app/models/crypto.py` and
`app/middleware/session.py` fall back to a loudly-logged ephemeral
per-process key when the env var is unset, so a fresh checkout/CI run still
boots and passes tests with zero setup, at the documented cost of not
surviving a process restart in that fallback mode.

